  "market_context": "Bearish daily bias on YM1!; price swept a prior high (liquidity sweep), formed a turtle soup (closed back inside range), then developed inversion, change in state of delivery, breaker block, and fair value gap confluence, leading to continuation lower.",
  "key_observation": "Price swept a high (triggering buy-side liquidity), closed back inside the range (turtle soup), then formed an inversion, change in state of delivery, and breaker block—confirming a bearish reversal setup for continuation to the lows.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identified a sweep of a prior high (liquidity grab) followed by a close back inside the range, forming a turtle soup (step one of reversal).",
    "Step 2: Observed an inversion forming as price closed through the fair value gap that created the swept high.",
    "Step 3: Confirmed change in state of delivery via a down-close candle closing below the series of up-close candles, establishing a bearish order block.",
    "Step 4: Noted breaker block formation and a new fair value gap overlapping the order block and inversion zone, creating confluence for short entries.",
    "Step 5: Anticipated continuation lower toward prior lows and internal range liquidity (FVGs), with a propulsion block forming off the reversal structure."
  ],
  "outcome": "Price continued lower after the reversal confirmation, reaching the targeted lows; trade taken short with 2R+ reward.",
  "lessons": "A bearish reversal is strongest when multiple ICT elements align—turtle soup, inversion, change in state of delivery, and breaker block—but focusing on 1–2 key confirmations (e.g., CISD + inversion) improves execution. Sweep of high must be followed by closure inside range to validate reversal.",
